We are moving through the most famous sermon perhaps ever given. Sermon on the mount delivered by Jesus as written in the book of Matthew

Matthew was an outcast jew and former tax collector that followed Jesus and became one of his 12 apostles

last week we covered the law in chapter 5 verses 17-20

This week we're covering verses 21-26 where Jesus talks about anger


--> Read verses 21-22

When Jesus says "you have heard that it was said" 

While he's not saying that what was said is wrong, he's clarifying proper interpretation

In a way, by saying "you have heard it was said", Jesus is saying that people have received bad teaching

You heard this but im telling you the truth. I'm going to clarify the misinterprations that have been offered to you by the scribes and pharisees

Jesus states the 6th of the ten commandments: You shall not murder

Murder is the outward behaviour of killing another individual

Not murdering others is a fairly simple and easy commandment to uphold

Then in verse 22 Jesus elevates the standard by saying that it's not enough to not murder people

Those who murder will be liable to judgement, but in addition, everyone who is angry with his brother is also liable to judgement

Those who insult their brother will be liable to judgement

Those who call someone a fool will be liable to the hell of fire

Jesus is saying that God's intent behind the 6th commandment goes far deeper than not killing people

The intent applies to the deepest level of our thoughts and feelings towards other

If you insult someone or are angry with someone, the intent is the same as murder. The action isn't the same but the intent is sinful and we should hold our intent to the same standard as our behaviours

The scribes and pharisees were teaching that unrighteous actions lead us to judgement

Jesus is saying that unrighteous attitudes and thoughts, while not the same as unrighteous actions, are such as much sins as the actions

Jesus is offering a deeper, more complete understanding of God's commandments than what was tought by the religious teachers of the day

Jesus is saying that obedience to the command against murder begins with eliminating anger in our hearts for our brother. Not just blood brother, any fellow believer, relative or someone we are close to

To be unrighteously angery with someone makes us liable to God's judgement

What justifies anger? That requires discernment and honesty

The clarification Jesus is making here is that while God cares about our actions, he also cares about our heart. Our attitudes and thoughts

If man is created in the image of God, killing a man means killing a creation of God

Likewise, insulting or calling someone worthless is also calling God's creation worthless

Keeping a righteous heart and mind is just as important in obeying God as maintaining righteous behaviours

Once again, Jesus sets a higher standard and expectation for those who follow him


God cares about our behaviour but even more than tha, he cares about the disposition of our heart

Many people can have good behaviour with wicked hearts. Not murdering anyone but being angry at the world

If your heart transforms, your behaviour follows

Righteous behaviour may not always mean righteous heart. Righteous thoughts 

Religion attempts to change people from the ouside in. Jesus helps people from the inside out

Follow Jesus and he will work on your heart





--> Read verses 23-24







You've heard it said that you shall not kill but I'm telling you that having hatred for someone is like killing them in your heart

Jesus is raising the bar. Setting a higher standard

It's not enough to just not take a life. Don't kill people in your heart with hate

Jesus is telling us that to hate someone in our heart is a symptom of the same problem as murder which is anger

Jesus is saying not to insult people. That isn't righteous behaviour and it leads to damnation

When you have conflict with someone, do your part to make things right. Strive to reconciliation

When you hold hate in your heart, you hold yourself in your own prison and you won't get out until you release that 

it's not just about murder, it's about the condition of your heart

If you have a wicked heart filled with hate but dont murder anyone, it's not ok


--> Read verses 25-26

Paid the last penny. Prison of anger. Remain in the prison until all of the anger has been addressed and let go





